DOCKER COMMANDS
    - [docker images] This command lists all Docker images stored on your system, showing details like repository name, tag, image ID, creation date, and size. 
    It helps you see what images you have and identify ones you might want to remove. 
    - [docker inspect] This command provides detailed information about a specific image or container, including configuration, environment variables, and layers. 
    It’s useful when you need deeper technical details.
        command format [docker inspect <image_id>]
    - [docker rmi] This command removes (deletes) a Docker image from your system to free up space. You can only remove images that are not being used by any containers.
        command format [docker rmi <image_id>]
    - [docker system prune] This command cleans up your Docker environment by removing unused data such as stopped containers, unused images, and networks. 
    It’s a quick way to free up space.
    - [docker ps] This command shows all currently running containers on your system, helping you monitor what’s active.
    - [docker stop] This command stops one or more running containers using their container IDs.
        command format [docker stop <container_id>]
    - [docker rm] This command permanently removes stopped containers from your system, helping keep things clean and organized.
        command format [docker rm <container_id>]